				\begin{document}$$ {\frac{{\partial (\varepsilon {\kern 1pt} \rho \,{\mathbf{v}})}}{\partial \,t}} + \nabla \cdot (\varepsilon {\kern 1pt} \rho \,{\mathbf{vv}}) = - \varepsilon \;\nabla p + \nabla \cdot (\varepsilon \;{\varvec{\uptau}}) + \varepsilon {\mathbf{g}} - {\frac{\mu }{\alpha }}\;{\mathbf{v}} $$\end{document}</tex-math><graphic xlink:href="449_2010_469_Article_Equ15.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>where <bold>v</bold> it is the velocity vector in the pores of the bed, <italic>&#x3C1;</italic> is the liquid density, <italic>p</italic> is the pressure, <bold>&#x3C4;</bold> is the stress tensor, <bold>g</bold> is the gravity vector and &#x3B1; is the permeability coefficient of the bed, given by the expression resulting from the Karman&#x2013;Kozeny model [<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR1">7</xref>]:<disp-formula id="Equ16"><label>13</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M16">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ \alpha = {\frac{{(2R_{\text{p}} \varepsilon )^{2} }}{90\;(1 - \varepsilon )}} $$\end{document}</tex-math><graphic xlink:href="449_2010_469_Article_Equ16.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>The equation of mass preservation (continuity equation) may be written as:<disp-formula id="Equ17"><label>14</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M17">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$ {\frac{{\partial (\varepsilon {\kern 1pt} \rho )}}{\partial \,t}} + \nabla \cdot (\varepsilon {\kern 1pt} \rho \,{\mathbf{v}}) = 0 $$\end{document}</tex-math><graphic xlink:href="449_2010_469_Article_Equ17.gif" position="anchor"/></alternatives></disp-formula>The boundary conditions are as follows:<disp-formula id="Equ18"><label>15a</label><alternatives><tex-math id="M18">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
